The Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA) is an American trade association representing the Major film studio#Current|six major film studios of Cinema of the United States|Hollywood, and streaming service giant, Netflix. Founded in 1922 as the Motion Picture Producers and Distributors of America (MPPDA), its original goal was to ensure the viability of the American film industry. In addition, the MPAA established guidelines for film content which resulted in the creation of the Motion Picture Production Code|Production Code in 1930. This code, also known as the Hays Code, was replaced by a voluntary Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|film rating system in 1968, which is managed by the Classification and Rating Administration (CARA).

More recently, the MPAA has advocated for the Film|motion picture and television industry, with the goals of promoting effective copyright protection, reducing Copyright infringement#"Piracy"|piracy, and expanding market access. It has long worked to curb copyright infringement, including recent attempts to limit the sharing of copyrighted works via peer-to-peer file-sharing networks and by streaming from pirate sites. Former United States Ambassador to France Charles Rivkin is the current chairman and CEO of the MPAA.

History

=Foundation and early history: 1922–29=

The MPAA was founded as the Motion Picture Producers and Distributors of America (MPPDA) in 1922 as a trade association of member motion picture companies. At its founding, MPPDA member companies produced approximately 70 to 80 percent of the films made in the United States.<ref name=NYT22a>cite news |title=Ultimatum by Hays to Purify Movies |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1922/06/05/archives/ultimatum-by-hays-to-purify-movies-producers-and-distrihuters-join.html |work=The New York Times |date=5 June 1922 |accessdate=1 February 2013</ref> Former United States Postmaster General|Postmaster General Will H. Hays was named the association's first president.<ref name=Kimono>cite book |title=The Dame in the Kimono: Hollywood, Censorship, and the Production Code |last1=Leff |first1=Leonard J. |last2=Simmons |first2=Jerold L. |year=2001 |publisher=University Press of Kentucky |location= |isbn=0813190118 |page= |pages= |url= </ref>

The main focus of the MPPDA in its early years was on producing a strong public relations campaign to ensure that Hollywood remained financially stable and able to attract investment from Wall Street, while simultaneously ensuring that American films had a "clean moral tone".<ref name=NYT22a /><ref name=EvenNews22>cite news |title=Hays Attacks Censors; Says Film Men O.K. |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EhdLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IiENAAAAIBAJ&dq=motion%20picture%20producers%20and%20distributors%20of%20america&pg=2733%2C7216162 |work=The Evening News |date=26 May 1922 |accessdate=1 February 2013</ref> The MPPDA also instituted a code of conduct for Hollywood's actors in an attempt to govern their behavior offscreen.  Finally, the code sought to protect American film interests abroad by encouraging film studios to avoid racist portrayals of foreigners.<ref name=Kimono /><ref name=Spokesman24>cite news |title=Czar of Movies Hits Censorship |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Np5XAAAAIBAJ&sjid=t_MDAAAAIBAJ&dq=motion%20picture%20producers%20and%20distributors%20of%20america&pg=5826%2C734859 |work=The Spokesman-Review |date=25 January 1924 |accessdate=1 February 2013</ref>

From the early days of the association, Hays spoke out against public Censorship in the United States#Film censorship|censorship,<ref name="Spokesman24"/><ref name=NYT22b>cite news |title=Hays Says Public Censors Will Fail |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1922/07/25/archives/hays-says-public-censors-will-fail-declares-american-principle-of.html |work=The New York Times |date=25 July 1922 |accessdate=1 February 2013</ref> and the MPPDA worked to raise support from the general public for the film industry's efforts against such censorship.<ref name=ProvNews22>cite news |title=Will Hays, Pledging Motion Picture Industry to Clean Pictures, Asks Public to Aid War on Evil Films |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WFBbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QVANAAAAIBAJ&dq=motion%20picture%20producers%20and%20distributors%20of%20america&pg=4100%2C1398046 |work=Providence News |date=6 July 1922 |accessdate=1 February 2013</ref> Large portions of the public opposed censorship, but also decried the lack of morals in movies.<ref name=Black96/>

At the time of the MPPDA's founding, there was no national censorship, but some state and municipal laws required movies to be censored, a process usually oveseen by a local censorship board.<ref name=Black96/> Thus, in certain locations in the U.S., films were often edited to comply with local laws regarding the onscreen portrayal of violence and sexuality, among other topics. This resulted in negative publicity for the studios and decreasing numbers of theater goers, who were uninterested in films that were sometimes so severely edited that they were incoherent.<ref name=Kimono /> In 1929, more than 50 percent of American moviegoers lived in a location overseen by such a board.<ref name=Black96/>

In 1924, Hays instituted "The Formula", a loose set of guidelines for filmmakers, in an effort to get the movie industry to self-regulate the issues that the censorship boards had been created to address. "The Formula" requested that studios send synopses of films being considered to the MPPDA for review. This effort largely failed, however, as studios were under no obligation to send their scripts to Hays's office, nor to follow his recommendations.<ref name=Black96>cite book |author=Gregory D. Black |title=Hollywood Censored: Morality Codes, Catholics, and the Movies |year=1996 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0521565928 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ybKqnNNR7hwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Hollywood+Censored:+Morality+Codes,+Catholics,+and+the+Movies&hl=en&sa=X&ei=hIweUZuEJsHe0QG6zoHgBg&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAA |accessdate=15 February 2013</ref>

In 1927, Hays oversaw the creation of a code of "Don'ts and Be Carefuls" for the industry.<ref name=Black96 /> This list outlined the issues that movies could encounter in different localities. Hays also created a Studio Relations Department (SRD) with staff available to the studios for script reviews and advice regarding potential problems. Again, despite Hays' efforts, studios largely ignored the "Don'ts and Be Carefuls," and by the end of 1929, the MPPDA received only about 20 percent of Hollywood scripts prior to production,<ref name=Kimono /> and the number of regional and local censorship boards continued to increase.<ref name=Black96/>

=Production Code: 1930–34=

In 1930, the MPPDA introduced the Motion Picture Production Code|Production Code, sometimes called the "Hays Code". The Code consisted of moral guidelines regarding what was acceptable to include in films.<ref name=TeleHerald30>cite news |title=Movie Industry to Bar Obscenity and Crime Scenes, Plan |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-K9FAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Pb0MAAAAIBAJ&dq=motion%20picture%20producers%20and%20distributors%20of%20america&pg=3907%2C1202519 |work=The Telegraph-Herald and Times-Journal |date=2 April 1930 |accessdate=1 February 2013</ref> Unlike the "Dont's and Be Carefuls", which the studios had ignored, the Production Code was endorsed by studio executives.<ref name=Kimono /> The Code incorporated many of the "Don'ts and Be Carefuls" as specific examples of what could not be portrayed. Among other rules, the code prohibited inclusion of "scenes of passion" unless they were essential to a film's plot; "pointed profanity" in either word or action; "sex perversion"; justification or explicit coverage of adultery; sympathetic treatment of crime or criminals; dancing with "indecent" moves; and white slavery.<ref name=Calgary30>cite news |title=Producers Adopt Code of Conduct For Screen Shows |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WyRkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WHsNAAAAIBAJ&dq=motion%20picture%20producers%20and%20distributors%20of%20america&pg=3606%2C4315324 |work=The Calgary Daily Herald |date=1 April 1930 |accessdate=1 February 2013</ref> Because studio executives had been involved in the decision to adopt the code, MPPDA-member studios were more willing to submit scripts for consideration. However, the growing economic impacts of the Great Depression of the early 1930s increased pressure on studios to make films that would draw the largest possible audiences, even if it meant taking their chances with local censorship boards by disobeying the Code.<ref name=Kimono />

In 1933 and 1934 the National Legion of Decency|Catholic Legion of Decency, along with a number of Protestant and women's groups, launched plans to boycott films that they deemed immoral.<ref name=Bernstein00>cite book |author=Matthew Bernstein |title=Controlling Hollywood: Censorship and Regulation in the Studio Era |year=2000 |isbn=0813527074 |publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dEYoT857G8UC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Controlling+Hollywood:+Censorship+and+Regulation+in+the+Studio+Era&hl=en&sa=X&ei=eIseUamHDaa00AHX1oH4Bg&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA |accessdate=15 February 2013</ref> In order to avert boycotts which might further harm the profitability of the film industry, the MPPDA created a new department, the Production Code Administration (PCA), with Joseph Breen as its head. Unlike previous attempts at self-censorship, PCA decisions were binding—no film could be exhibited in an American theater without a stamp of approval from the PCA,<ref name=Black96 /> and any producer attempting to do so faced a fine of $25,000.<ref name=Kimono /> After ten years of unsuccessful voluntary codes and expanding local censorship boards, the studio approved and agreed to enforce the codes, and the nationwide "Production Code" was enforced starting on July 1, 1934.<ref name=Black96/>

=War years: 1935–45=

In the years that immediately followed the adoption of the Code, Breen often sent films back to Hollywood for additional edits, and in some cases, simply refused to issue PCA approval for a film to be shown.<ref name=Kimono /><ref name=LewistonTrib34>cite news |title=Pictures Purged |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-Z5fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wzEMAAAAIBAJ&dq=motion%20picture%20producers%20and%20distributors%20of%20america&pg=3861%2C4395343 |work=Lewiston Morning Tribune |date=15 July 1934 |accessdate=1 February 2013</ref> At the same time, Hays promoted the industry's new focus on wholesome films<ref name=SpokaneChron35>cite news |title=Newest Pictures Based on Classics |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=atRXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_fQDAAAAIBAJ&dq=motion%20picture%20producers%20and%20distributors%20of%20america&pg=2505%2C6402892 |work=Spokane Daily Chronicle |date=26 March 1935 |accessdate=1 February 2013</ref> and continued promoting American films abroad.<ref name=MilJournal36>cite news |title=Will Hays Gets Italy to Lift Film Blockage |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PHYxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_yEEAAAAIBAJ&dq=will-hays&pg=6885%2C5924504 |work=The Milwaukee Journal |date=25 November 1936 |accessdate=19 February 2013</ref>

For nearly three years, studios complied with the Code. By 1938, however, as the threat of war in Europe loomed, movie producers began to worry about the possibility of decreased profits abroad. This led to a decreased investment in following the strictures of the code, and occasional refusals to comply with PCA demands.<ref name=Kimono /> That same year, responding to trends in European films in the run-up to the war, Hays spoke out against using movies as a vehicle for propaganda.<ref name=PittPress38>cite news |title=Hays Scores Propaganda On Screens |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LE0bAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D0wEAAAAIBAJ&dq=motion%20picture%20producers%20and%20distributors%20of%20america&pg=4508%2C6029095 |work=The Pittsburgh Press |date=30 March 1938 |accessdate=1 February 2013</ref> In 1945, after 24 years as president, Hays stepped down from his position at the MPPDA, although he continued to act as an advisor for the Association for the next five years.<ref name="SpokesReview45">cite news |title=Eric Johnston to Rule Movies |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vipWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=o-QDAAAAIBAJ&dq=will-hays%20and%20johnston&pg=6105%2C4697631 |work=The Spokesman-Review |date=20 September 1945 |accessdate=19 February 2013</ref>

=Johnston era: 1945–63=

In 1945 the MPPDA hired Eric Johnston, four-time president of the United States Chamber of Commerce, to replace Hays.<ref name=SpokChron45>cite news |title=Johnston Named Motion Picture Czar |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7NZYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jvUDAAAAIBAJ&dq=will-hays%20and%20johnston&pg=6668%2C3421898 |work=Spokane Daily Chronicle |date=19 September 1945 |accessdate=19 February 2013</ref> During his first year as president, Johnston rebranded the Motion Picture Producers and Distributors of America as the Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA).<ref name=Kimono />

He also created the Motion Picture Export Association (MPEA) to promote American films abroad by opposing production company monopolies in other countries.<ref name=Lewis02p37>cite book |author=Jon Lewis |title=Hollywood V. Hard Core: How the Struggle Over Censorship Saved the Modern Film Industry |year=2002 |isbn=0814751423 |publisher=NYU Press |pages=37–38 </ref><ref name=NYT46>cite news |title=Movies Begin to Fight Foreign Monopolies |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/04/05/archives/movies-begin-to-fight-foreign-monopolies.html |work=New York Times |date=5 April 1946 |accessdate=12 April 2013</ref> In 1947 the MPEA voted to discontinue film shipments to Britain after the British government imposed an import tax on American films.<ref name=Deseret47>cite news |title=Film Group Votes Ban On Movies for England |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MggpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nU0DAAAAIBAJ&dq=mpaa%20johnston&pg=6849%2C767130 |work=The Deseret News |date=7 August 1947 |accessdate=12 April 2013</ref> Johnston negotiated with the British government to end the tax in 1948, and film shipments resumed.<ref name=NYT48>cite news |title=MPEA Approves Johnston's Agreement; To Lift Film Embargo After British Ratify |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/03/19/archives/mpea-approves-johnstons-agreement-to-lift-film-embargo-after.html |work=New York Times |date=19 March 1948 |accessdate=16 April 2013</ref>

In 1956, Johnston oversaw the first major revision of the Production Code since it was created in 1930. This revision allowed the treatment of some subjects which had previously been forbidden, including abortion and the use of narcotics, so long as they were "within the limits of good taste". At the same time, the revisions added a number of new restrictions to the code, including outlawing the depiction of blasphemy and mercy killings in films.<ref name=RG56>cite news |title=Motion Picture Code Made 'More Flexible' |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JRFWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cOIDAAAAIBAJ&dq=mpaa%20johnston&pg=6763%2C3434436 |work=Eugene Register Guard |date=17 December 1956 |accessdate=12 April 2013</ref>

Johnston was well-liked by studio executives, and his political connections helped him function as an effective liaison between Hollywood and Washington.<ref name=Valenti07p271>cite book |author=Jack Valenti |title=This Time, This Place |year=2007 |isbn=9780307346650 |publisher=Three Rivers Press |location=New York |page=271 </ref> In 1963, while still serving as president of the MPAA, Johnston died of a stroke.<ref name=Petersburg63>cite news |title=Eric Johnston Dies at 66 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uJtPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sVIDAAAAIBAJ&dq=eric-johnston&pg=2746%2C970120 |work=St. Petersburg Times |date=23 August 1963 |accessdate=12 April 2013</ref> For three years, the MPAA operated without a president while studio executives searched for a replacement.<ref name=MPAAHistory>cite web|url=http://mpaa.org/about/history |title=History of the MPAA |work=MPAA.org |publisher=Motion Picture Association of America |accessdate=23 April 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621235047/http://www.mpaa.org/about/history |archivedate=June 21, 2013 </ref>

=Valenti era: 1966–2004=
multiple image
| align     = right
| direction = vertical
| image1    = JackValenti19.JPG
| width1    = 220
| caption1  = Jack Valenti was the president of Motion Picture Association of America for 38 years.
| image2    =
| width2    = 220
| caption2  = Former U.S. Ambassador to France and Assistant Secretary of State Charles Rivkin became the chairman and CEO of the MPAA in 2017

The MPAA hired Jack Valenti, former aide to President Lyndon B. Johnson|Lyndon Johnson, as president of the MPAA in 1966.<ref name=Clabaugh04>cite news |title=Valenti retires, Glickman named Hollywood's Washington man |author=Jeff Clabaugh |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/stories/2004/06/28/daily27.html?page=all |work=Washington Business Journal |date=1 July 2004 |accessdate=2 April 2013</ref> In 1968, Valenti replaced the Production Code with Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|a system of voluntary film ratings, in order to limit censorship of Hollywood films and provide parents with information about the appropriateness of films for children.<ref name=Valenti07>cite book |author=Jack Valenti |title=This Time, This Place |year=2007 |isbn=9780307346650 |publisher=Three Rivers Press |location=New York |pages=302–306 </ref> In addition to concerns about  protecting children,<ref name=StPete68>cite news |title=Film Ratings System Adopted By Industry |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=U4dQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PlwDAAAAIBAJ&dq=mpaa%20film%20ratings%20system&pg=5849%2C5695295 |work=St. Petersburg Times |date=8 October 1968 |accessdate=12 March 2013</ref> Valenti stated in his autobiography that he sought to ensure that American filmmakers could produce the films they wanted, without the censorship that existed under the Production Code that had been in effect since 1934.<ref name=Valenti07/>

In 1975 Valenti established the Film Security Office, an anti-piracy division at the MPAA, which sought to recover unauthorized recordings of films to prevent duplication.<ref name=Clabaugh04 /><ref name=WindsorStar75>cite news |title=Movie industry fights film piracy |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HUU_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=DVIMAAAAIBAJ&dq=jack%20valenti%20piracy&pg=2594%2C4176001 |work=Windsor Star |date=14 April 1975 |accessdate=18 April 2013</ref> Valenti continued to fight piracy into the 1980s, asking Congress to install chips in VCRs that would prevent illegal reproduction of video cassettes,<ref name=McCloskey86>cite news |title=Movie Producers Want Anti-Copy Device On VCR Makers |author=Bill McCloskey |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=3SJD-HRB0-0011-83BF&csi=304478&oc=00240&perma=true |work=The Associated Press |date=23 September 1986 |accessdate=6 March 2013</ref> and in the 1990s supported law enforcement efforts to stop bootleg recording|bootleg distribution of video tapes.<ref name=Billboard91>cite news |title=MPAA Bags Some 50,000 Bogus Vids in N.Y. Bust |author=Paul Verna |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=3SJD-WP60-002S-H0VG&csi=5545&oc=00240&perma=true |work=Billboard |date=18 May 1991 |accessdate=6 March 2013</ref> Valenti also oversaw a major change in the ratings system that he had helped create—the removal of the "X" rating, which had come to be closely associated with pornography. It was replaced with a new rating, "NC-17", in 1990.<ref name=Gerosa90>cite news |title=How the X Got Axed |author1=Melina Gerosa |author2=Anne Thompson |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318334,00.html |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=12 October 1990 |accessdate=18 April 2013</ref><ref name=SpokeChron90>cite news |title=Big-name Hollywood directors join battle over MPAA |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=01lYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BPoDAAAAIBAJ&dq=valenti%20mpaa&pg=7058%2C4089237 |work=The Spokesman-Review|Spokane Chronicle |date=31 July 1990 |accessdate=18 April 2013</ref>

In 2001 Valenti established the Digital Strategy Department at the MPAA to specifically address issues surrounding digital cinema|digital film distribution and piracy.<ref name=Clabaugh04 /><ref name=Wright>cite news |title=Jack Valenti Steps Down from MPAA/MPA |author=Guy Wright |work=Digital Producer Magazine |date=1 July 2004 </ref>

=Modern era: 2004–present=
After serving as president of the MPAA for 38 years, Valenti announced that he would step down in 2004.<ref name=BBC04>cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3861263.stm |title=Hollywood chief Valenti to retire |date=2 July 2004 |work=BBC |accessdate=2 April 2013</ref> In September of that year, he was replaced by former United States Secretary of Agriculture|Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman.<ref name="Clabaugh04"/> During his tenure, Glickman focused on tax issues, content protection efforts, and increasing U.S. studios' access to international markets.<ref name=Mullins09>cite news |title=Glickman says he'll step down in 2010 |author=Anne Schroeder Mullins |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/news/politics-politico/glickman-says-hell-step-down-in-2010-362652/ |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=19 October 2009 |accessdate=2 April 2013</ref> He led lobbying efforts that resulted in $400 million in federal tax incentives for the movie industry, and also supported a law which created federal oversight of anti-piracy efforts.<ref name=Puzzanghera09>cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/20/business/fi-ct-glickman20 |title=Search starts for MPAA chief Dan Glickman's replacement |author1=Jim Puzzanghera |author2=Claudia Eller |date=20 October 2009 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=16 April 2013</ref> Glickman stepped down in 2010.<ref name=Mullins09 /><ref name=Sandoval10>cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1023_3-10439572-93.html |title=MPAA's Dan Glickman steps down |author=Greg Sandoval |date=22 January 2010 |work=CNET |accessdate=2 April 2013</ref>

After a search which lasted over a year, the MPAA hired former U.S. Senator Chris Dodd to replace Glickman in March 2011.<ref name=Verrier11>cite news |title=MPAA hires former Sen. Dodd as head |author1= Richard Verrier |author2=Jim Puzzanghera |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/mar/02/business/la-fi-ct-mpaa-dodd-20110302 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=2 March 2011 |accessdate=2 April 2013</ref> In his role as president, Dodd focused on content protection, trade, and improving Hollywood's image.<ref name=McClinktock12>cite news |title=MPAA Chief Christopher Dodd Says SOPA Debate Isn't Over, Defends Hosting Harvey Weinstein Even as He Attacked Over 'Bully' |author=Pamela McClintock |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mpaa-christopher-dodd-sopa-bully-harvey-weinstein-ratings-308359 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=5 April 2012 |accessdate=2 April 2013</ref> He traveled to China in 2011 in an effort to encourage the Chinese government to both crack down on piracy and further open its film market.<ref name=Landreth11>cite news |title=MPAA's Chris Dodd Presses China to Open Film Market |author=Jonathan Landreth |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mpaas-chris-dodd-presses-china-200784 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=13 June 2011 |accessdate=2 April 2013</ref> A settlement of a long-argued World Trade Organization complaint, coupled with Dodd's efforts, contributed to the United States' agreement with China in 2012 to open China's film market to more Hollywood films and to increase U.S. studios' share of box office revenues in China.<ref>cite news|last1=Faughnder|first1=Ryan|title=Shake-up at the MPAA. Hollywood's chief lobbyist, Chris Dodd, to be replaced by Charles Rivkin|url=http://beta.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-dodd-mpaa-exit-20170428-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|date=28 April 2017</ref> In addition to this agreement with China, the U.S. signed more than 20 memos of understanding with foreign governments regarding the enforcement of intellectual property rights during Dodd's tenure at the MPAA.<ref>cite news|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title=Chris Dodd Stepping Down As Chairman Of MPAA; Charles Rivkin To Take Over|url=http://deadline.com/2017/04/chris-dodd-stepping-down-chairman-of-mpaa-motion-picture-association-of-america-1202079427/|work=Deadline|date=28 April 2017</ref>

In 2011, the MPAA supported the passage of the Stop Online Piracy Act (SOPA) and PROTECT IP Act (PIPA).<ref name=Block12>cite news |title=MPAA Chairman Chris Dodd Speaks Out Against 'Blackout' Protest of SOPA and PIPA |author=Alex Ben Block |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mpaa-chris-dodd-blackout-piracy-sopa-282755 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=17 January 2012 |accessdate=2 April 2013</ref> After the two bills were shelved in early 2012, Dodd indicated that Hollywood might cut off campaign contributions to politicians who failed to support anti-piracy efforts in the future.<ref>cite news|title=Chris Dodd warns of Hollywood backlash against Obama over anti-piracy bill|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/01/19/exclusive-hollywood-lobbyist-threatens-to-cut-off-obama-2012-money-over-anti.html|work=Fox News|date=19 January 2012</ref>

In 2012, the MPAA launched the Diversity and Multicultural Outreach program, as part of an effort to increase diversity in the television and film industry both through employment and representation on screen.<ref>cite web|title=Inclusion & Multicultural Outreach|url=https://www.mpaa.org/inclusion-multicultural-outreach/#outreach|publisher=Motion Picture Association of America|accessdate=16 February 2018</ref> Since its inception, the Diversity and Multicultural and Outreach group has conducted outreach and partnered with more than 20 multicultural groups and national civil rights organizations in sponsoring film screenings, festivals, and other diversity-themed events.<ref>cite news|last1=Garcia|first1=Tonya|title=MPAA Partners With "Dope" For American Black Film Festival Opening Night|url=http://madamenoire.com/537798/mpaa-dope-american-black-film-festival-opening-night/|work=MadameNoire|date=3 June 2015</ref>

Throughout his tenure at the MPAA, Dodd also highlighted the need for movie studios to embrace technology as a means of distributing content.<ref name=Block11>cite news |title=Chris Dodd Pushes Back Against Hollywood Vs. Technology Criticisms In SMPTE |author=Alex Ben Block |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chris-dodd-mpaa-technology-smpte-253753 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=2 April 2013</ref>

In June 2017, the MPAA supported the launch of the Alliance for Creativity and Entertainment (ACE), a coalition of entertainment companies, including the six major studios, Netflix and Amazon (company)|Amazon, that would draw on the MPAA's resources in an effort to reduce online piracy through research and legal efforts.<ref>cite news|last1=Lieberman|first1=David|title=Hollywood And Digital Companies Forge Global Anti-Piracy Alliance|url=http://deadline.com/2017/06/hollywood-digital-companies-forge-global-antipiracy-alliance-1202112346/|work=Deadline|date=13 June 2017</ref>

Former U.S. diplomat and Assistant Secretary of State for Economic and Business Affairs Charles Rivkin succeeded Chris Dodd as CEO on September 5, 2017, and as chairman effective December 6, 2017.

Film rating system

Main|Motion Picture Association of America film rating system

In 1968, the MPAA established the Code and Rating Administration, or CARA (later renamed the Classification and Rating Administration), which began issuing ratings for films exhibited and distributed commercially in the United States to help parents determine what films are appropriate for their children.

Since the  motion picture rating system|rating system was first introduced in November 1968, it has gone through several changes, including the addition of a PG-13 rating.<ref name=Coe68>cite news |title=Film Classification Starts Nov. 1 |author=Richard L. Coe |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ujwxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ogEEAAAAIBAJ&dq=mpaa%20film%20ratings%20system&pg=7248%2C5548739 |work=Toledo Blade |date=14 October 1968 |accessdate=12 March 2013</ref><ref name=Champlin70>cite news |title=Film Ratings Plan Will Be Revised |author=Charles Champlin |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WAscAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tloEAAAAIBAJ&dq=mpaa%20film%20ratings%20system&pg=6981%2C4372645 |work=The Victoria Advocate |date=29 January 1970 |accessdate=12 March 2013</ref> The ratings system is completely voluntary, and ratings have no legal standing.<ref name=Lipper90>cite news |title=At last, an adult decision |author=Hal Lipper |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=3SKP-CMT0-0060-215N&csi=11063&oc=00240&perma=true |work=St. Petersburg Times |date=29 September 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2013</ref><ref name=Richman03>cite news |title=Law limits some violent video games |author=Dan Richman |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Law-limits-some-violent-video-games-1115175.php |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |date=20 May 2003 |accessdate=10 May 2013</ref> Instead, theater owners enforce the MPAA film ratings after they have been assigned,<ref>cite news |title=CinemaCon: MPAA Tweaks Movie Ratings System in Wake of Newtown School Shooting |author=Pamela McClintock |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cinemacon-mpaa-tweaks-movie-ratings-440392 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=16 March 2013 |accessdate=10 May 2013</ref> with many theaters refusing to exhibit non-rated films.<ref name=McClintock12>cite news |title=Weinstein Co. to Release Unrated 'Bully' in Protest of 'R' |author=Pamela McClintock |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/weinstein-bully-unrated-rated-r-mpaa-304232 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=26 March 2012 |accessdate=9 May 2013</ref> An unrated film is often denoted by "NR", such as in newspapers, although this is not a formal MPAA rating.<ref>cite book |first=Daniel P. |last=Franklin |title=Politics and Film: The Political Culture of Film in the United States |year=2006 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=9781461641018 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=eQp4AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA153 153]</ref>

In 2006 the film ''This Film Is Not Yet Rated'' alleged that the MPAA gave preferential treatment to member studios during the process of assigning ratings,<ref name=Travers06>cite news |title=''This Film Is Not Yet Rated'' |author=Peter Travers |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/this-film-is-not-yet-rated-20060803 |work=Rolling Stone |date=3 August 2006 |accessdate=28 May 2013</ref> as well as criticizing the rating process for its lack of transparency. In response, the MPAA posted its ratings rules, policies, and procedures, as well as its appeals process, online.<ref name=McClintock07>cite news |title=MPAA, NATO reform ratings system |author=Pamela McClintock |url=https://variety.com/2007/film/news/mpaa-nato-reform-ratings-system-1117957535/ |work=Variety |date=16 January 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2013</ref>

According to a 2015 study commissioned by CARA, ninety-three percent of parents in the U.S. find the rating system to be a helpful tool.<ref>cite news|last1=McClintock|first1=Pamela|title=Movie Ratings: Sex Remains Top Concern for American Parents, Not Violence|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/movie-ratings-sex-remains-top-845507|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=3 December 2015</ref>

The ratings currently used by the MPAA's voluntary system are:<ref name=MPAARatings>cite web |url= http://www.mpaa.org/film-ratings/ |title=Film Ratings |work=MPAA.org |accessdate=4 August 2014</ref>

