! Rating !! Meaning !! MPAA's Explanation

|-

| align="center" | G || General Audiences || "Nothing that would offend parents for viewing by children."
On the box: "All ages admitted"

|-

| align="center" | PG || Parental Guidance Suggested || "Parents urged to give 'parental guidance.' May contain some material parents might not like for their young children."
On the box: "Some material may not be suitable for children"

|-

| align="center" | PG-13 || Parents Strongly Cautioned || "Parents are urged to be cautious. Some material may be inappropriate for pre-teenagers."
On the box: "Some material may be inappropriate for children under 13"

|-

| align="center" | R || Restricted || "Contains some adult material. Parents are urged to learn more about the film before taking their young children with them."
On the box: "Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian"

|-

| align="center" | NC-17|| Adults Only || "Clearly adult. Children are not admitted."
On the box: "No One 17 and Under Admitted"

|}

Members
The original members of the MPAA were the "Big Eight" film studios: Paramount Pictures, 20th Century Fox, Loews Cineplex Entertainment|Loews, Universal Pictures|Universal Studios, Warner Bros., Columbia Pictures, United Artists, and RKO Pictures.<ref name=Spring>cite book |last=Spring |first=Joel |title=Images of American Life |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kvWRWJrRePAC&pg=PA50&dq=founding+member+mppda&hl=en&sa=X&ei=o3o5UYvSNKbI2wWrkYCgCA&ved=0CGIQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=founding%20member%20mppda&f=false |accessdate=7 March 2013 |year=1992 |publisher=State University of New York Press |location=Albany |isbn=0791410706 |page=50 </ref> Two years later, Loews merged with Metro Pictures, Goldwyn Pictures, and Louis B. Mayer|Louis B. Mayer Productions to form Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer.<ref name="Movers and Shakers">cite book |title=Movers and Shakers: The 100 Most Influential Figures in Modern Business |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GPdNo2nVAFAC&pg=PA253&dq=metro+goldwyn+mayer+merger+form+mgm&hl=en&sa=X&ei=No9DUb-rOJKA2AWw2oCoCQ&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=metro%20goldwyn%20mayer%20merger%20form%20mgm&f=false |accessdate=14 March 2013 |year=2003 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc |isbn=0738209147 |page=253 </ref>

United Artists briefly resigned from the organization in 1956 over a ratings dispute, although they rejoined later in the decade.<ref name=AFI>cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=51583 |title=The Man with the Golden Arm |work=American Film Institute |accessdate=19 March 2013</ref> By 1966, Monogram Pictures|Allied Artists Pictures had joined the original members.<ref name=Vaughn>cite book |last=Vaughn |first=Stephen |title=Freedom and Entertainment: Rating the Movies in an Age of New Media |url=http://www.suu.edu/faculty/petersent/pdf/mpaaresearch.pdf |accessdate=7 March 2013 |year=2006 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=New York |isbn=0521676541 |page=23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712230400/http://www.suu.edu/faculty/petersent/pdf/mpaaresearch.pdf |archivedate=12 July 2014 |df= </ref> In the following decade, new members joining the MPAA included Embassy Pictures|Avco Embassy in 1975 and Walt Disney Studios (division)|Walt Disney Studios in 1979.<ref name=Weiler>cite news |first=A H |last=Weiler |title=Jack Valenti, pres of Motion Picture Assn of Amer... |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=3SJB-2MX0-0028-93DM&csi=6745&oc=00240&perma=true |newspaper=New York Times |date=26 January 1975 |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref><ref name=Arnold>cite news |first=Gary |last=Arnold |title=Film Notes |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=3S8G-BVX0-0009-W484&csi=8075&oc=00240&perma=true |newspaper=Washington Post |date=5 April 1980 |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref><ref name=NYT>cite news |title=Movie Group's Meeting At Cannes Is Canceled |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=3S8G-BFN0-0007-H3F3&csi=6742&oc=00240&perma=true |newspaper=New York Times |date=29 April 1986 |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref> The next year, Filmways became a MPAA member, but was later replaced in 1986 along with Avco Embassy when the De Laurentiis Entertainment Group and Orion Pictures joined the MPAA roster.<ref name=Arnold />

As of 1995, the MPAA members were MGM—which included United Artists after their 1981 merger, Paramount Pictures, Sony Pictures—which included Columbia and TriStar Pictures after their acquisition in 1989, 20th Century Fox,  Universal Studios, Walt Disney Studios, and Warner Bros.<ref name=Cook>cite book |last=Cook |first=David |title=Lost Illusions: American Cinema in the Shadow of Wtergate and Vietnam |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HVygqYMVP2wC&q=mgm+united+artist#v=snippet&q=mgm%20united%20artist&f=false |accessdate=7 March 2013 |year=2000 |publisher=University of California Press |location=Berkeley |isbn=0520232658 |page=21</ref><ref name=GT-DEX-1989-08>cite news|title=Sony to Buy Columbia, Says Americans Will Run Studio : 1st Sale of Film Maker to Japanese |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-09-27/news/mn-335_1_columbia-pictures-entertainment|accessdate=24 September 2012 |newspaper=latimes.com |date=27 September 1989</ref> Turner Entertainment joined the MPAA in 1995, but was purchased in 1996 by Time Warner.<ref name=Wharton>cite news |first=Dennis |last=Wharton |title=Turner Pix Joins MPAA |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=3S3M-F440-0006-000R&csi=140595&oc=00240&perma=true |newspaper=Daily Variety |date=25 January 1995 |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref><ref name=Fabrikant>cite news |first=Geraldine |last=Fabrikant |title=Holders Back Time Warner-Turner Merger |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/11/business/holders-back-time-warner-turner-merger.html |newspaper=New York Times |date=11 October 1996 |accessdate=14 March 2013</ref>

At the beginning of 2019, the MPAA's member companies were Paramount Pictures, Sony Pictures Entertainment, 20th Century Fox, Universal Studios, Walt Disney Studios, and Warner Bros.<ref>cite web |title=Who We Are – Our Story |publisher=Motion Picture Association of America |url=http://www.mpaa.org/our-story/ |accessdate=April 27, 2017</ref> Netflix was approved as a new member in January 2019, making it the first non-studio and streaming service to be part of the organization, and also filling a spot in the association filled by the impending completion of Disney's acquisition of 20th Century Fox.<ref>cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/netflix-advanced-talks-join-mpaa-1177926 | title = Netflix Becomes First Streamer to Join the Motion Picture Association of America | first = Pamela | last = McClintock | date = January 22, 2019 | accessdate = January 22, 2019 | work = The Hollywood Reporter </ref>

Content protection efforts
The MPAA's concerted efforts at fighting copyright infringement began in 1975 with the establishment of the Film Security Office, which sought to recover unauthorized recordings of films in order to prevent duplication.<ref name="Clabaugh04"/><ref name="WindsorStar75"/> The MPAA has continued to pursue a number of initiatives to combat illegal distribution of films and TV shows, especially in response to new technologies. In the 1980s, it spoke out against Videocassette recorder|VCRs and the threat that the MPAA believed they represented to the movie industry,<ref name=Marbach82>cite news |title=Putting the Bite On the Home VCR |author=William D. Marbach |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=3SJ4-FRJ0-0008-X3VM&csi=5774&oc=00240&perma=true |work=Newsweek |date=26 April 1982 |accessdate=6 March 2013</ref> with MPAA president Jack Valenti drawing a parallel between the threat of the VCR and that of the Boston Strangler.<ref name=Jones87>cite news |title=The invasion of the VCRs |author=Malcolm Jones |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=3SKP-90V0-0060-2035&csi=11063&oc=00240&perma=true |work=St. Petersburg Times |date=26 April 1987 |accessdate=6 March 2013</ref> In 1986, the MPAA asked Congress to pass a law that would require VCRs to come equipped with a chip to prevent them from making copies.<ref name="McCloskey86"/> Legal efforts at stopping homemade copies of broadcast television largely ended, however, when the United States Supreme Court ruled that such copying constituted fair use.<ref name=CommDaily87>cite news |title='Distortion' Charged; DAT Anticopy Technology Debated At Joint Hill Hearing |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=3TVV-HHR0-0019-30PX&csi=6944&oc=00240&perma=true |work=Communications Daily |date=3 April 1987 |accessdate=6 March 2013</ref>

The MPAA continued to support law enforcement efforts to stop bootleg recording|bootleg production and distribution of videos tapes and laserdiscs into the 1990s,<ref name="Billboard91"/><ref name=Goldstein94>cite news |title=Picture This |author=Seth Goldstein |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TAgEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=RA1-PA53&dq=MPAA%20laserdiscs&pg=RA1-PA53#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=Billboard |date=21 May 1994 |accessdate=19 March 2013</ref> and in 2000 took successful legal action against individuals posting DVD Digital rights management#DRM and film|decryption software on the Internet in Universal City Studios, Inc. v. Reimerdes.<ref name=Costello00>cite news |title=Content de-scrambling fought |author=Sam Costella |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=414V-TG80-00J5-J3D9&csi=169977&oc=00240&perma=true |work=InfoWorld Daily News |date=6 September 2000 |accessdate=8 March 2013</ref> Following the release of RealDVD—an application that enabled users to make copies of DVDs—RealNetworks sued the DVD Copy Control Association and the major studios in 2008 over the legality of the software, accusing them of violating the Sherman Antitrust Act.<ref name=Sandoval09>cite news |title=RealNetworks accuses MPAA of antitrust violations |author=Greg Sandoval |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1023_3-10240490-93.html |work=CNET |date=13 May 2009 |accessdate=28 May 2013</ref> The judgment found there were no grounds for the antitrust claim and dismissed RealNetworks, Inc. v. DVD Copy Control Association, Inc.|the suit.<ref name=Kravets10>cite news |title=Judge Slams MPAA 'Cartel' Allegations |author=David Kravets |url=https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2010/01/judge-slams-mpaa-cartel-allegations/ |work=Wired |date=11 January 2010 |accessdate=28 May 2013</ref> The court later found that the RealNetworks product violated the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA).<ref>cite news|last1=Goel|first1=Vindu|title=RealNetworks Drops Fight to Sell DVD Copying Software|url=https://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/03/03/realnetworks-drops-fight-to-sell-dvd-copying-software/?mtrref=en.wikipedia.org&gwh=BE322A0601B9731550114F9E6090EACE&gwt=pay|work=The New York Times|date=3 March 2010</ref>

The MPAA has continued to support law enforcement efforts to prevent illegal distribution of copyrighted materials online.<ref name=Lieberman13>cite news |title=MPAA Cheers Prison Sentence For Leader Of Internet Piracy Ring |author=David Lieberman |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/01/mpaa-imagine-group-justice-department-conviction-sentencing/ |work=Deadline.com |date=4 January 2013 |accessdate=22 April 2013</ref> The MPAA and its British counterpart, the Federation Against Copyright Theft (FACT), also funded the training of Lucky and Flo, a pair of Labrador Retrievers, to detect polycarbonates used in the manufacturing of DVDs.<ref name=Kirk06>cite web |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/125679/article.html |title=MPAA Trains Dogs to Sniff Out Pirate DVDs |author=Jeremy Kirk |date=11 May 2006 |work=PCWorld |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref>

=Online file sharing=
In the early 2000s, the MPAA began focusing its efforts to curb copyright infringement specifically on peer-to-peer file sharing, initially using a combination of educational campaigns<ref name=Atkinson03>cite news |title=Music piracy persists at Boston U., nationwide despite lawsuits |author=Dan Atkinson |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=4B6F-HJW0-00K4-105J&csi=172244&oc=00240&perma=true |work=University Wire |date=10 December 2003 |accessdate=8 March 2013</ref> and cease and desist letters to discourage such activity. In the first six months of 2002, the MPAA sent more than 18,000 such letters to internet service providers to forward to users engaged in copyright infringement.<ref name=Woolley02>cite news |title=Shiver me timbers: Online bootlegs bane of entertainment industry |author=Simon Woolley |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=4600-8XW0-015H-052Y&csi=244819&oc=00240&perma=true |work=Townsville Bulletin/Townsville Sun |date=3 June 2002 |accessdate=8 March 2013</ref>

In late 2004, the MPAA changed course and filed lawsuits in a concerted effort to address copyright infringement on a number of large online file-sharing services, including BitTorrent and eDonkey network|eDonkey.<ref name=Locklear04>cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/uncategorized/2004/12/4467-2/ |title=MPAA lawsuits target BitTorrent, eDonkey and Direct Connect networks |author=Fred Locklear |date=14 December 2004 |work=Ars Technica |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref> The following year, the MPAA expanded its legal actions to include lawsuits against individuals who downloaded and distributed copyrighted material via peer-to-peer networks.<ref name=Johnson05>cite news |title=MPAA Anti-Piracy Lawsuits Target Individuals |author=Bary Alyssa Johnson |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=4H0K-M4X0-01KX-14V2&csi=262320&oc=00240&perma=true |work=PC Magazine |date=29 August 2005 |accessdate=6 March 2013</ref>

The MPAA also played a role in encouraging the Government of Sweden|Swedish government to conduct the Pirate Bay raid|a raid of the Pirate Bay file-sharing website in May 2006.<ref name=Mennecke06>cite web |url=http://www.slyck.com/story1227.html |title=Sweden Pressured to take Pirate Bay Action |author=Thomas Mennecke |date=20 June 2006 |work=Slyck.com |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref> Swedish officials have acknowledged that part of the motivation for the raid was the threat of sanctions from the World Trade Organization, along with a letter from the MPAA.<ref name=Ahrens06>cite news |title=U.S. Joins Industry in Piracy War |author=Frank Ahrens |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/06/14/AR2006061402071.html |work=The Washington Post |date=15 June 2006 |accessdate=6 March 2013</ref><ref name=Ewing06>cite web |url=http://www.thelocal.se/4128/20060621/#.UTdo1nyY4RE |title=US threatened Sweden with sanctions over piracy |author=Adam Ewing |date=21 June 2006 |work=The Local |accessdate=6 March 2013</ref>

In 2013 the Center for Copyright Information unveiled the Copyright Alert System, a system established through an agreement between the MPAA, the Recording Industry Association of America, and five of the USA's largest internet service providers.<ref name=Miller13>cite news |title=MPAA-Backed Copyright Alert System Unveiled |author=Sean J. Miller |url=http://www.backstage.com/news/mpaa-backed-copyright-alert-system-unveiled/ |work=Back Stage |date=26 February 2013 |accessdate=22 April 2013</ref> The system used a third-party service to identify content being distributed illegally. Users were then informed that their accounts were being used for possible copyright infringement and were provided with information about ways to get authorized content online.<ref>cite news |title=The new copyright alert system is running |author=Sarah Laskow |url=http://www.cjr.org/cloud_control/cas_system_already_in_action.php?page=all |work=Columbia Journalism Review |date=28 February 2013 |accessdate=22 April 2013</ref> Users who received multiple notices of infringement faced "mitigations measures," such as temporary slowing of their Internet service, but the system did not include termination of subscriber accounts. Subscribers facing such action had a right to appeal to the American Arbitration Association.<ref name=CASFAQs>cite web |url=http://www.copyrightinformation.org/resources-faq/copyright-alert-system-faqs/ |title=Copyright Alert System FAQs |work=copyrightinformation.org |publisher=Center for Copyright Information |accessdate=25 April 2013</ref> In January 2017, the Copyright Alert System was discontinued.  While no official reason was given, the MPAA's general counsel stated that the system had not been equipped to stop repeat infringers.<ref>cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Ted|title=Internet Service Providers, Studios and Record Labels Call It Quits on Copyright Alert System|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/copyright-alerts-piracy-mpaa-comcast-att-1201971756/|work=Variety|date=27 January 2017</ref>

On December 24, 2014, the Sony Pictures hack revealed that following a lawsuit in which the MPAA won a multimillion judgment against Hotfile, a file hosting website, the MPAA colluded with Hotfile to misrepresent the settlement so that the case would serve as a deterrent. The settlement was previously believed to be $80 million and was widely reported; however, Hotfile only paid the studios $4 million and agreed to have the $80 million figure recorded as the judgment and the website shut down.<ref>cite news|last1=Van der Sar|first1=Ernesto|title=MPAA Secretly Settled With Hotfile for $4 Million, Not $80 Million|url=https://torrentfreak.com/mpaa-secretly-settled-hotfile-4-million-80-million-141224/|work=Torrentfreak|date=24 December 2014</ref><ref>cite web|url=http://www.neowin.net/news/sony-email-leak-has-uncovered-the-truth-behind-mpaa-and-hotfile-dispute|title=Sony email leak has uncovered the truth behind MPAA and Hotfile dispute|publisher=</ref><ref>cite web|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20141224/06321429517/sony-hack-reveals-that-mpaas-big-80-million-settlement-with-hotfile-was-lie.shtml|title=Sony Hack Reveals That MPAA's Big '$80 Million' Settlement With Hotfile Was A Lie|publisher=</ref>

In a case resolved in 2015, the MPAA and others supported the United States International Trade Commission (ITC)'s decision to consider electronic transmissions to the U.S. as "articles" so that it could prevent the importation of digital files of counterfeit goods. While the case being considered by the ITC involved dental appliances, the ITC could have also used such authority to bar the importation of pirated movies and TV shows from rogue foreign websites that traffic in infringing content.<ref>cite news|last1=Gardner|first1=Eriq|title=With the MPAA Watching, ITC Says Case About Teeth Won't Bring Down the Internet|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/mpaa-watching-itc-says-case-775397|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=19 February 2015</ref>  The Federal Circuit Court of Appeals took up the matter, and ultimately ruled against the ITC.<ref>cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Ted|title=MPAA Warns Appellate Ruling Could Limit Ability to Fight Digital Piracy|url=https://variety.com/2015/biz/news/mpaa-digital-goods-piracy-google-1201637501/|work=Variety|date=10 November 2015</ref>

In 2016, the MPAA reported Putlocker as one of the "top 5 rogue cyberlocker services" to the Office of the United States Trade Representative as a major piracy threat; the website was then blocked in the United Kingdom.<ref>cite news |last=Sandoval |first=Greg |date=31 March 2012 |title=MPAA wants more criminal cases brought against 'rogue' sites |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/mpaa-wants-more-criminal-cases-brought-against-rogue-sites/ |publisher=CNET |access-date=17 October 2016 </ref><ref>cite news |last=Prabhu |first=Vijay |date=17 October 2016 |title=Yet Another Video Streaming Service Bites The Dust, Putlocker Shuts Down |url=http://www.techworm.net/2016/10/putlocker-video-streaming-service-shuts.html |publisher=TechWorm |access-date=17 October 2016 </ref><ref>cite news |last=Bolton |first=Doug |date=26 May 2016 |title=Putlocker blocked in the UK by internet service providers after High Court order |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/putlocker-blocked-down-virgin-media-sky-internet-streaming-watch-online-videos-a7050056.html |publisher=''The Independent'' |access-date=17 October 2016 </ref>

Criticism and controversies
=Publicity campaigns=
The MPAA has also produced publicity campaigns to discourage piracy. The ''Who Makes Movies?'' advertising campaign in 2003 highlighted workers in the movie industry describing how piracy affected them. The video spots ran as trailers before movies, and as television advertisements.<ref name=Boliek03>cite news |title=H'wood steps up antipiracy fight |author=Brooks Boliek |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=4BG8-SXP0-01V4-X35T&csi=12015&oc=00240&perma=true |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=23 July 2003 |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref> In 2004, the MPAA began using the slogan "You can click, but you can't hide". This slogan appeared in messages that replaced file-sharing websites after they had been shut down through MPAA legal action.<ref name=BBC05>cite news |title=Movie body hits peer-to-peer nets |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/4256449.stm |work=BBC News |date=11 February 2005 |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref> It also appeared in posters and videos distributed to video stores by the MPAA.<ref name=Hernandez04>cite news |title=MPAA Files Piracy Suits |author=Greg Hernandez |url=http://w3.nexis.com/new/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=4DTP-V1K0-TWDH-T3C9&csi=157105&oc=00240&perma=true |work=The Daily News of Los Angeles |date=17 November 2004 |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref> Also in 2004, the MPAA partnered with the Intellectual Property Office of Singapore to release You Wouldn't Steal a Car|a trailer shown before films in theaters equating piracy with theft.<ref name=IPOS04>cite web|url=http://www.ipos.gov.sg/main/newsroom/media_rel/mediarelease1_270704.html |title=Be HIP at the Movies |author= |date=27 July 2004 |work=Intellectual Property Office of Singapore |accessdate=6 March 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924044120/http://www1.ipos.gov.sg/main/newsroom/media_rel/mediarelease1_270704.html |archivedate=September 24, 2008 </ref> The trailer was later placed at the beginning of the video on many DVDs in such a way that it could not be bypassed (not being able to skip or fast-forward), which triggered criticism and a number of parodies.<ref name=Rohrer09>cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/8106805.stm |title=Getting inside a downloader's head |author=Finlo Rohrer |date=18 June 2009 |work=BBC |accessdate=6 March 2013</ref>

In 2005, the MPAA commissioned a study to examine the effects of file sharing on movie industry profitability. The study concluded that the industry lost $6.1 billion per year to piracy, and that up to 44 percent of domestic losses were due to file sharing by college students. In 2008, the MPAA revised the percentage of loss due to college students down to 15 percent, citing human error in the initial calculations of this figure. Beyond the percentage of the loss that was attributable to college students, however, no other errors were found in the study.<ref name=Pope08>cite news|title=MPAA admits mistake on downloading study |author=Justin Pope |url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/98009/page/1 |work=Newsweek |date=23 January 2008 |accessdate=5 March 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207045516/http://www.newsweek.com/id/98009/page/1 |archivedate=February 7, 2008 </ref>

In 2015, theaters began airing the MPAA's "I Make Movies" series, an ad campaign intended to combat piracy by highlighting the stories of behind-the-scenes employees in the film and television industry.<ref>cite news|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title=MPAA to Run 'I Make Movies' Ads at AMC Theaters, Local Cinema Chains|url=https://www.thewrap.com/mpaa-to-run-i-make-movies-ads-at-amc-theaters-local-cinema-chains/|work=The Wrap|date=25 June 2015</ref>  The series pointed audiences to the MPAA's "WhereToWatch" website (later dubbed "The Credits")<ref>cite web|url=https://www.thecredits.org/|website=mpaa.org|title=The Credits|accessdate=16 February 2018</ref> which provides attention to the behind-the-scenes creativity involved in making movies.

=Accusations of copyright infringement=
The MPAA itself has been accused of copyright infringement on multiple occasions. In 2007, the creator of a Blog software|blogging platform called Forest Blog accused the MPAA of violating the license for the platform, which required that users link back to the Forest Blog website. The MPAA had used the platform for its own blog, but without linking back to the Forest Blog website. The MPAA subsequently took the blog offline, and explained that the software had been used on a test basis and the blog had never been publicized.<ref>cite news|title=MPAA: We Were Only Testing Forest Blog|url=https://torrentfreak.com/mpaa-we-were-only-testing-forest-blog|work=Torrentfreak|date=28 February 2007</ref><ref name=Thomas07>cite web|url=http://www.bit-tech.net/news/bits/2007/02/19/MPAA_violates_software_license/ |title=MPAA violates software license |author=Brett Thomas |date=19 February 2007 |work=bit-tech.net |accessdate=5 March 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110183631/http://www.bit-tech.net/news/bits/2007/02/19/MPAA_violates_software_license/ |archivedate=November 10, 2013 </ref>

Also in 2007, the MPAA released a software toolkit for universities to help identify cases of file sharing on campus. The software used parts of the Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu Linux distribution, released under the GNU General Public License|General Public License, which stipulates that the source code of any projects using the distribution be made available to third parties. The source code for the MPAA's toolkit, however, was not made available. When the MPAA was made aware of the violation, the software toolkit was removed from their website.<ref name=Paul07>cite news |title=MPAA's University Toolkit hit with DMCA takedown notice after GPL violation |author=Ryan Paul |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2007/12/mpaas-university-toolkit-hit-with-dmca-takedown-notice-after-gpl-violation/ |work=Ars Technica |date=4 December 2007 |accessdate=5 March 2013</ref>

In 2006, the MPAA admitted having made illegal copies of ''This Film Is Not Yet Rated'' (a documentary exploring the MPAA itself and the history of its MPAA film rating system|rating system)<ref name=LATimes>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060130093854/http://www.latimes.com/business/custom/cotown/cl-et-mpaa24jan24,0,2188275.story MPAA finds itself accused of piracy], by John Horn; at the ''Los Angeles Times'' (via archive.org); published January 24, 2006; retrieved June 11, 2014</ref> — an act which ''Ars Technica'' explicitly described as hypocrisy<ref name=ArsTech>[https://arstechnica.com/uncategorized/2006/01/6036-2/ MPAA admits to unauthorized movie copying], by Eric Bangeman, at ''Ars Technica''; published January 24, 2006; retrieved June 11, 2014</ref> and which Roger Ebert called "rich irony".<ref name=Ebert>[http://www.rogerebert.com/festivals-and-awards/sundance-7-film-ratings-exposed Sundance #7: Film ratings exposed!], by Roger Ebert; at RogerEbert.com; published January 26, 2006; retrieved June 11, 2014</ref> The MPAA subsequently claimed that it had the legal right to copy the film despite this being counter to the filmmaker's explicit request, because the documentary's exploration of the MPAA's ratings board was potentially a violation of the board members' privacy.<ref name=LATimes/>

